REASONS FOR JUDGMENT

MCNAB J

This matter concerns the applicant mother, Ms Scriven born in 1984 (“the mother”) and the respondent father, Mr Preston born in 1973 (“the father”). The parties seek parenting orders in respect of the child, X born in 2019 (“the child”) and an alteration of their property interests.
These reasons concern parenting matters only. The mother corresponded with the Court seeking that reasons and orders as to the parenting matters be provided as soon as practicable where she was required to travel overseas but such depended on the orders made by the Court. The Court will be in a position to make orders and provide reasons in respect of property matters shortly.

BACKGROUND

The parties married in 2018, although they agree that cohabitation commenced in February 2017. The date of separation is disputed. The father asserts that separation occurred in April 2021 while it is the mother’s case that separation occurred on 6 December 2021. I find that the parties separated on 6 December 2021. The father was required to leave the family home as a result of the terms of an intervention order obtained on the application of the police after an incident in April 2021 which will be dealt with below. The father returned to the family home in November 2021 at which point he was demanding that the mother sign a binding financial agreement. When she refused to do this, on 5 December 2021 he sent her a text where he stated:[1]
I’ve got someone new starting next week so there really is no need for us to talk anymore. We are officially separated and I will start whatever proceedings are necessary to get a divorce from you. I gave you an option for me to come back home but you are to greedy and made it harder. Now that’s off the table. Good luck with being a single mother and getting a job.
I find that separation occurred on 6 December 2021. In the period between April 2021 and December 2021, the father had sent the mother text messages expressing a desire to return to the family home and the parties communicated as husband and wife.[2] The mother continued to work in the business conducted by the father and helped to try and manage his gambling expenditure.
The mother characterises the latter years of the parties’ relationship to be marred by family violence where the father was regularly abusive towards her, including in front of the child.[3] The father denies such and contends that the relationship was tumultuous and he was subjected to physical and verbal assaults.[4]
The child has been diagnosed with autism spectrum disorder and ADHD. He has also been diagnosed with childhood a speech disorder.
The father has four other children from previous relationships, being:
(a) Ms L born in 1998;

(b) Mr N born in 1999;

(c) Mr M born in 2008; and

(d) O born in 2012.

The mother has a child from a previous relationship, Y born in 2010. Y has always lived with the mother on a full-time basis. Y has been diagnosed with ADHD and autism.[5]
At the commencement of cohabitation, the parties moved into a property at P Street, Suburb Q, Victoria [...] until they purchased and moved into the property at R Street, Suburb S, Victoria [...] (“[Suburb S] property”) in February 2018.[6] The mother has remained living at the Suburb S property with the child since separation.

Procedural History

This matter has an extraordinary history in this Court given the time that the proceedings have been on foot. The mother filed an Initiating Application on 10 May 2022 seeking orders as to property. The father filed a Response to Initiating Application on 7 June 2022 seeking orders as to parenting and property. The mother filed a Reply to Response to Initiating Application on 14 October 2022 seeking orders that the father spend no time with the child.
On 7 June 2022, orders were made by consent for the father to pay the mother the sum of $40,000 with such payment to be characterised by the trial judge. The father was restrained by injunction from selling or further encumbering any of the parties’ assets and all restate estate was to be valued by a joint single valuer. The father was also restrained from withdrawing more than $10,000 per month from the businesses’ bank account. As to parenting, there was an Independent Children’s Lawyer (“ICL”) appointed.
On 8 December 2022, orders were made by consent for the child to live with the mother and spend time with the father as agreed by the parties in writing and for each of the parties to attend for hair and drug alcohol testing. The parties were also to attend upon Ms B (“the Family Report writer”), for a Short Form Family Report. All extant applications for litigation funding were adjourned to 16 December 2022.
On 16 December 2022, orders were made for the father to pay the mother the sum of $50,000 to be characterised by the trial judge and the mother’s costs fixed in the sum of $5,000.
On 23 December 2022, the mother filed an Application for Contempt in circumstances where she contended that the father failed to pay her the sums referred to in the orders of 16 December 2022 and the costs of the mother’s hair and drug alcohol testing while also drawing from the businesses’ accounts in breach of the orders of 7 June 2022.
On 6 January 2023, the father filed an Application for Review in relation to the orders of 16 December 2022.
On 20 January 2023, the Family Report writer prepared the Short Form Family Report.
On 10 March 2023, any time between the father and the child was suspended. The period for the father to comply with hair and drug alcohol testing was extended and the father was ordered to attend upon Dr C for a psychological assessment and report.
On 11 April 2023, Dr C prepared a psychological risk evaluation of the father. Dr C expressed that despite identified issues with the father, these would not necessarily be significant risk factors in direct parenting of the child. Dr C noted that the father’s insight into his psychological vulnerabilities is limited and that he is unlikely to engage effectively in treatment.
On 29 June 2023, orders were made discharging the orders of 16 December 2022.
On 20 July 2023, the mother’s contempt application was adjourned to a final hearing with priority on 16 November 2023. The mother says that she withdrew her application as she did not want to further delay the substantive matters.
On 10 August 2023, the father filed an Application in a Proceeding seeking unsupervised time with the child.
On 28 August 2023, orders were made by consent for, among other things, the parties to facilitate the child’s attendance upon the Family Report writer for an updated Family Report.
On 22 November 2023, all previous parenting orders were discharged. The child was ordered to live with the mother and spend supervised time with the father for up to one hour once a month for three occasions. Thereafter, the time would increase to up to two-three hours once a month. The father’s time with the child was dependent on the father undergoing hair and drug alcohol testing. The father did not spend time with the child in accordance with these orders as the father did not comply with the terms of the order in relation to hair and drug alcohol testing.
On 8 May 2024, the matter was listed for final hearing before Judge J Young on 21 October 2024 for an estimated hearing time of four days. On that date, orders were made by Judge J Young transferring the matter to the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia (Division 1). Further orders were made that day by consent providing the mother with $60,000 from the net proceeds of the property at T Street, Suburb U, VIC [...], by way of partial property settlement. The balance of the funds were to be placed in a controlled money interest bearing account by the mother’s solicitors pending final orders.
On 10 December 2024, Bennett J made orders dismissing the father’s oral application for a non-single expert witness, for interim spend time orders and for costs of a further business valuation. Orders were also made for the parties to obtain an up-to-date valuation of the business and for the father to make, file and serve an affidavit explaining any references in his bank statements of payments made between 11-16 April 2024 totalling $106,300.
The matter was listed for final hearing on 10 February 2025. On 13 February 2025, the final hearing was vacated, and judgment was reserved as to the father’s application for interim time with the child as well as striking out the reports of the Family Report writer. On 19 March 2025, the father’s applications were dismissed and the mother’s costs reserved.
On 25 March 2025, the matter was listed for final hearing on 30 June 2025 for an estimated hearing time of 10 days.
On 16 April 2025, the mother filed an Application in a Proceeding for litigating funding. On 8 May 2025, orders were made for the mother to receive by way of partial property settlement the sum of $172,000 from the funds held in the trust account of her solicitors. The father was ordered to pay the costs of the application fixed in the sum of $5,675.
On 30 June 2025, the first day of the hearing, the Court was informed that the father no longer sought the services of counsel briefed to appear on his behalf and his solicitor made an application to file a Notice of Ceasing to Act which was granted. The father was informed by the Court that he would be required to appear on his own behalf. On the second day of the hearing, the father’s former solicitor attended the hearing, notwithstanding the events of the day prior. The father informed the Court that he sought the assistance of his previous solicitor for the final hearing. The father then made an application for an adjournment so as to allow him to brief new counsel. The matter was adjourned part-heard until 7 July 2025 with the costs of the mother and the ICL being reserved.
On 11 July 2025, the matter was adjourned part-heard to 20 August 2025. The father sought a different adjournment date as he had pre-planned travel to the Gold Coast for a holiday. This request was denied. On 7 August 2025, he filed an Application in a Proceeding again seeking that proceedings be adjourned to a different date so as to allow him to travel. Orders were made on 8 August 2025 dismissing this application.
On 22 August 2025, orders were made for written submissions to be filed and served in relation to the financial aspect of the proceedings.
Since the commencement of these proceedings, there have been nearly 350 documents and 80 subpoena filed with around 35 hearings.

PROPOSALS

The mother seeks that there be no time or communication between the father and the child and that she have sole decision-making authority for all major long-term issues in relation to the child. She also seeks that the child’s surname be changed.
The father seeks orders that the parties have joint decision-making authority for all major long-term issues in relation to the child and that he spend time with the child graduating to unsupervised time, subject to conditions, each alternate weekend from 10:00am on Saturday until 6:00pm on Sunday as well as special occasions and during school holidays.
The ICL supported the mother’s position of no time and the provision of cards, letters and gifts. As to the child’s surname, the ICL supported the change if the Court made orders for no time between the father and the child.

EVIDENCE

The mother, by way of her Outline of Case filed 26 June 2025, seeks to rely upon:
(a) affidavit of Ms Scriven filed 20 June 2025;

(b) updated Financial Statement filed 20 June 2025;

(c) affidavit of Ms V filed 3 February 2025;

(d) affidavit of Ms Scriven filed 18 October 2024;

(e) Further Amended Initiating Application filed 24 September 2024;

(f) affidavit of Ms Scriven filed 24 September 2024;

(g) affidavit of Ms W (annexing section 50 notice) filed 24 June 2024;

(h) DFFH section 69ZW Response dated 28 February 2024;

(i) affidavit of the Family Report writer filed 15 November 2023;

(j) affidavit of Dr C filed 23 May 2023;

(k) affidavit of the Family Report writer filed 9 February 2023;

(l) DFFH section 67Z Response dated 4 January 2023;

(m) DFFH section 67Z Response dated 24 October 2022; and

(n) Various subpoenaed documents – listed to be provided at the commencement of the final hearing.

The father, by way of his Outline of Case filed 4 July 2025, seeks to rely upon:
(a) consolidated trial affidavit of Mr Preston filed 3 February 2025;

(b) Financial Statement filed 11 December 2024;

(c) affidavit of Mr Preston regarding Ms L’s home, filed pursuant to Order 9 Of Bennett J, December 2024 filed 11 December 2024;

(d) Amended Response filed 14 October 2024;

(e) affidavit of Mr Z filed 14 October 2024;

(f) affidavit of Mr AA filed 14 October 2024;

(g) affidavit of Mr J filed 14 October 2024;

(h) affidavit of Ms L filed 14 October 2024;

(i) affidavit of Ms BB filed 14 October 2024;

(j) Ms V Forensic Accounting report Business Valuation filed 2 September 2024 and 3 February 2025;

(k) Dr CC Toxicologist Report, attaching his report dated 15 August 2024 that is annexed to the father’s trial affidavit of 15 October 2024 at annexure MRP-9 at page 90-97 of that affidavit, and is referred to at paragraph 117 of that affidavit filed 4 February 2025;

(l) Dr C report dated 1 May 2023 and affidavit filed 23 May 2023;

(m) reports of the Family Report writer dated 9 February 2023 and 15 November 2023; and

(n) email from Ms Scriven to DFFH on 7 July 2021 to DFFH which father provided to Court dated 7 July 2021;

The Independent Children’s Lawyer, by way of their Outline of Case filed 25 June 2025, relies upon:
(a) Section 69ZW Report prepared by the Department of Families, Fairness and Housing (second s 69ZW Report) dated 28 February 2024.

(b) Family Report prepared by the Family Report writer dated 30 October 2023; and

(c) Psychological Assessment and Report and Family Violence Risk Evaluation and Report, in relation to the father, prepared by Dr C dated 1 May 2023;

(d) Short Form Family Report prepared by the CCE dated 20 January 2023;

(e) section 69ZW Report prepared by the Department of Families, Fairness and Housing (first s 69ZW Report) dated 4 January 2023;

(f) Response to Notice of Risk Report prepared by the Dpeartment of Families, Fairness and Housing (s 67Z Report) dated 24 October 2022;

(g) Confidential Court Report, Protection Application Report, in support of protection application, Melbourne Children’s Court (Children’s Court Report 1) dated April 2021; and

(h) Confidential Court Report, Protection Application Report, Recommendations (Disposition report in support of protection application), Melbourne Children’s Court (Children’s Court Report 2) dated April 2021.

Some of the documents relied upon relate to property matters.

RELEVANT LAW

In deciding whether to make a particular parenting order in relation to the children, I must regard the best interests of the child as the paramount consideration.[7]
Section 60CC(2) of the Act sets out the list of matters that the Court must consider in determining what is in the children's best interests.
Orders in respect of children are made under Part VII of the Act, where the meaning of a “parenting order” is defined (s 64B). The Court may make such parenting orders as it thinks proper (s 65D(1)), within the context of the objects of the legislation (s 60B). The objects of Part VII of the Family Law Act 1975 (“the Act”) are to ensure that the best interests of children are met, including by ensuring their safety, and to give effect to the Convention on the Rights of the Child of 20 November 1989.[8] My decision is guided by those objects.
The Act confirms that safety includes safety from family violence, abuse, neglect or other harm.[9] Family violence and abuse are defined in the Act as “violent, threatening or other behaviour by a person that coerces or controls a member of the person’s family or causes the family member to be fearful”.[10] Examples of such behaviour include assaults, repeated derogatory taunts, intentionally damaging property, unreasonably withholding financial support and preventing a family member from keeping connections with his or her family and friends.
The Explanatory Memorandum indicates further that “other harm” allows me to consider whether these children are affected by issues such as inter-parental conflict.[11]
“Safety” is not defined in the Act. I note that the Explanatory Memorandum to the Family Law Amendment Act 2023 states that s 60B(a) of the Act is “intended to make it clear to all users of the Family Law Act that safety is a fundamental consideration when considering the best interests of the child.”[12] It goes on to state that Courts should consider “what arrangements would encourage or support a removal, reduction or avoidance of harm”.[13]
In considering these matters I must include consideration of:
(a) any history of family violence, abuse or neglect involving the child or a person caring for the child; and

(b) any family violence order that applies or has applied to the child or a member of the child’s family.[14]

Parental responsibility for children is vested in their parents (s 61C(1)), regardless of whether they live together or are separated (s 61C(2)), but that situation only applies whilst ever no order is made to change it (s 61C(3) and s 61D). Parental responsibility is defined to encompass all duties, powers, responsibilities and authority conferred by law upon parents (s 61B).
I am not required to resolve every controversy raised by the parties’ evidence or to refer to all the evidence raised by them. I refer to that evidence which is relevant to the issues that must be determined by the Court (Whisprun Pty Ltd v Dixon [2003] HCA 48; (2003) 200 ALR 447 at [62]. See also Housing Commission (NSW) v Tatmar Pastoral Co Pty Ltd [1983] 3 NSWLR 378).
In Isles & Nelissen [2022] FedCFamC1A 97; (2022) FLC 94-092 the Full Court held that findings of fact, where possible, are made to the requisite standard of proof but the assessment of unacceptable risk is a prospective exercise which involves the Court considering all of the circumstances, including but not limited to any findings or lack of findings, to assess whether there is a possibility of future harm arising and the severity of such.

CONSIDERATION

Section 60CC(2)(a)

What arrangements would promote the safety of the child (including safety from being subjected to, or exposed to, family violence, abuse, neglect, or other harm) of the child and each person who has care of the child (whether or not a person has parental responsibility for the child)

Section 60CC(2A)

In considering the matters set out in paragraph (2)(a) the Court must include consideration of any history of family violence, abuse or neglect involving the child or a person caring for the child (whether or not the person had parental responsibility for the child) and any family violence order that applies or has applied to the child or a member of the child’s family

Family Violence

The mother gives evidence that she and the child were subject to significant family violence throughout the marriage. The mother gives the following evidence regarding incidents of family violence including that:[15]
(a) the father would verbally abuse the mother and the child calling her names such as “cunt”;

(b) the father would throw household items at her throughout the marriage out of anger. This includes an incident when the child was a few months old and the father threw a kettle of boiling water at the mother while she was holding the child;

(c) when the mother was about four months pregnant with the child, the father became enraged in the car with the mother when Ms L informed him over the phone that he had been embarrassing the night before when he was at the mother and Ms L’s workplace in a drunken state. This caused the father to begin smashing the interior of the car and, once he got home, the back door and the television;

(d) the father would pressure the mother to perform sexual acts and verbally abused her when she refused;

(e) there was an occasion where the mother had an asthma attack and the father laughed instead of assisting her;

(f) there were two occasions where the parties had a disagreement and went out for dinner thereafter and the father ordered food with peanuts knowing peanuts caused the mother to have an anaphylactic reaction;

(g) on 31 October 2020, after the father had been drinking, he threatened to kill the maternal grandfather after the mother refused to give him $120,000 to gamble with. He then grabbed her by the throat while she was carrying the child and pushed her to the ground;

(h) in April 2021, there was a physical altercation at the workplace between the parties and the mother fell down a flight of stairs;

(i) the father would physically abuse the family dog; and

(j) the father left voice messages verbally abusing the mother.

The mother asserts that the family violence perpetrated by the father and feelings of control have continued post-separation and she gives evidence of the father:[16]
(a) issuing proceedings in VCAT seeking a sale of the Suburb S property;

(b) reporting the businesses’ vehicle as stolen (which was in the possession of the mother and her only motor vehicle), including contacting tow truck drives to have the vehicle impounded;

(c) stopping the direct debits previously established to meet expenses;

(d) in breach of court orders, failing to pay for the mother’s drug and alcohol testing;

(e) failing to provide disclosure;

(f) on 19 October 2023, the father parked his vehicle in the driveway of the maternal grandfather’s property; and

(g) after 20 October 2023, the mother sighted another of the father’s vehicles on the street where the maternal grandfather resided, with the vehicle moving every couple of days.

There is also a considerable history of family violence orders involving the parties.

Father’s Gambling

The mother says that during the relationship she became aware that the father had a severe issue with drinking and gambling. Part of the mother’s role, on her account, was to help prevent the father from gambling from August 2020 until October 2021 when she worked in the business. The mother’s evidence was that the violence throughout this period became worse and that the father became enraged by the financial restraints which he was agreeable to.[17]
The mother says that initially she was able to limit the father’s gambling by giving him access to a bank account in her name, but as the father’s abuse progressed, he used more than $2,000 per week and she was unable to control his gambling.[18] She asserts that between 30 September 2020 and 30 September 2021, the father gambled at least $295,988.10 using her account.[19]
In relation to the bank account associated with the business, the mother notes that between December 2021 until 31 March 2022, the father spent in excess of $780,000 with gambling organisations.[20] From his personal bank account, the father spent between 19 July 2022 until 31 December 2022, $371,153.18 with gambling organisations. From 1 January 2023 until 13 July 2023, this figure was $184,757.70.[21]
With DD Pty Ltd alone, the father spent $676,977 on his account from February 2022 until July 2022. Between February 2023 and July 2023, this figure was $408,811.[22]
The mother gave evidence about the father’s gambling habits saying that he was always gambling and most days he would gamble until he had no funds left. I accept that the mother tried to assist the father in this respect. It is plain from the tendered correspondence that family violence against the mother escalated during this time. This includes on 11 September 2021 where the father asked the mother to transfer him $1,000 which she denied and to which he replied, “our house my money not yours alone what’s your problem, you might not like what I do next”.[23]

31 October 2020 Incident

As noted above, this incident arose, on the mother’s account, after the father had been drinking and she refused to provide him with funds to gamble. I accept the mother’s evidence that on 31 October 2020 the father grabbed her bag and then grabbed her by her throat while she was holding the child when she refused to provide him with funds to gamble with. The father’s version of events differed, but he accepted that he had grabbed the mother by the throat and that it was not his “finest moment”.

April 2021 Incident

The mother tendered into evidence CCTV footage of a physical altercation between the parties at the business in April 2021.[24] The footage depicts the father in a heightened manner, towering over the mother while she was seated and arguing in an animated manner in the mother’s face. The father then proceeds to leave but takes from the mother’s bag what appears to be a purse. The mother desperately attempts to retrieve it from the father, grabbing and holding the father. The mother, out of view of the footage, while still grappling with the father, falls down a set of stairs. The mother says that the father did take her purse from the bag which contained all of her cards,[25] which is evidence I accept. The father appeared to suggest during cross-examination that this was an incident of family violence perpetrated on him. I reject this. Not only does this demonstrate his lack of insight into matters of family violence, I find that this is but one incident of family violence that the mother was subjected to when working in the business and the father’s behaviour in the footage is congruent with his previous conduct, not only against the mother, but towards the public, which will be canvassed further below, but includes an incident where he had to be restrained at a sports club.[26]
In relation to the incident at the sports club, the father gave evidence that in July 2021, he had been drinking at the club with a group of his friends over an afternoon. The female bar attendant refused him service (presumably because he was intoxicated) and he became enraged. There was then an altercation involving other people within the venue. The father claimed it was “a bit of fun” which involved rolling around on the floor. He was banned from the premise as a result of that altercation. I do not accept that it was “a bit of fun” but that it was in fact a brawl instigated by the father after a drinking session.

Verbal Abuse

I also accept the mother’s evidence that she was verbally abused by the father. She tendered various text messages between her and the father, many relating to finances, the business and gambling.[27] The messages are replete with the father’s threats and verbal abuse. There are also voice recordings which were tendered which contained the father verbally abusing and denigrating the mother.[28] The terms of the abuse are extreme and the voice messages contain the father saying to the mother the following in a very aggressive manner:
(a) on 11 October 2021, “Why are you such a negative fucking cunt”;

(b) on 26 October 2021, “Answer your fucking phone cunt”

(c) on 4 November 2021, “You’re a fucking cunt... you’re a fucking rat... I want you out of me fucking business too cunt”;

(d) on 18 November 2021, “It’s not abuse when you’re holding fucking other people’s shit. It is not abuse you fuckwit”; and

(e) on 18 November 2021, “Why don’t you answer your phone there shit cunt”.

The mother gave further evidence that on 4 November 2021, as noted above, when the father returned to the Suburb S property after the police intervention order obtained in November 2020 had expired, the father demanded that the mother sign a binding financial agreement. The mother was given a deadline of 3 December 2021 to decide whether or not to sign the agreement. At the time that she was provided with the agreement she was told by the father that if she did not sign that document that she would not have a job or livelihood to provide for the children, that he would remove her from the property and ensure that he left her with nothing. Text messages sent by the father confirm the mother’s evidence in relation to the threats made by the father. Around the time of separation, the father sent:[29]
You’re a fuckwit we now will have to get lawyers take another 200k off our total

There was no need for me to get angry today but you’re the only piece of shit cunt back and make everything in the world harder than what it is and we get so fucking angry I would have to have fucking rocks in my head to put myself through that fucking torture to come back to you forget everything don’t come into work tomorrow forget the agreement you’re a piece of fucking shit.

Today is my deadline next week there will be a new Sheila in the office. You can get fucked

I’m not spending another minute on it. Too late for you now
This also includes the following:[30]
If you can’t get over everything and move on, this is a good deal. I’m fed up with all your make it harder bullshit. If we can’t get this done. We are finished. And I’m stubborn and if we start finalising the courts I will make it my business to give you as little as possible no more agreements. Then [X] will miss out on having me there if you put me through bullshit

Mother’s Letter to DFFH

It was feature of the mother cross-examination by counsel for the father to a raise a letter that she had sent DFFH in July 2021 where she claimed not to be frightened of the father and stated that there were effectively no issues within the marriage.[31] The mother explained that the father pressured her into writing the letter as she was fearful of her life.
I accept the mother’s evidence in that regard and such conduct aligns with my findings of family violence perpetrated against her.
Generally, the father was hostile towards DFFH. The mother gives evidence that the father’s communication with the DFFH included him saying the following:[32]
(a) in May 2021, “with your lying report you can get stuffed” and “don’t bother contacting me again”;

(b) in July 2021, “I employ a dozen hard working aussies what have you got and what do you do? Kick people out of their homes you fucking shit cunt”;

(c) in July 2021, “you have made this too hard I am selling the house and divorcing my wife, we work together so she won’t have a job, I won’t see the kids. [Y] has an absent father and I am the only one he knows. I hope you can give them somewhere to live. Shove your fucking joke a court case up your ass. Lose my number and email and go get fucked you black cunt”; and

(d) in September 2021, “there’s no police charges because what you think happened didn’t you fuckwits, the black cunt [name omitted] who caused more problems couldn’t Evan stay the course and finish it off to see what damage he has caused so what do you think you fucking know”.

In general, I place little weight on any communication prior to separation which is said to be complimentary of the father by the mother. These communications were within the context of the family violence I have found.

Post-Separation

I also accept that the father continued to commit family violence post separation and during these proceedings whereby in October 2023, around the time of the parties attendance upon the Family Report writer for the purposes of the Family Report, the father parked his car in the driveway of the maternal grandfather’s house. His explanation for how his car was caused to be parked in the maternal grandfather’ house was unsatisfactory and rejected.

Past Conduct

The father presented as a man who had long-term issues with containing himself and as having been frequently before the courts over a long period for offences of violence.[33] In more recent years, he was before the courts on two occasions for crimes of violence against people who had come to his work premises to perform work.
One incident for which he appeared in the Magistrates’ Court in March 2022 involved the assault of a driver. The father claimed that there was a disagreement between him and the driver, and he told the driver to move his truck. The father then moved towards the truck to move it himself at which point the truck driver moved to stop him doing this. The father then struck the driver several times with a closed fist. In the course of giving evidence there was no suggestion of remorse or acknowledgement that what he had done was a serious criminal offence. The records from the Magistrates’ Court recorded a lack of remorse on the father’s part.
Another instance of violence in the workplace involved a technician who came to the work premises to repair some equipment. A disagreement developed and apparently the father was not happy with the approach of the technician and ordered him out of the premises. In his evidence, the father admitted pushing the technician and throwing his tools after him.
Significantly, these incidents occurred when he was at work and, according to his evidence, sober and clearheaded.

Family Violence Against the Father

The father made assertions that he was subjected to family violence committed by the mother. This, on the father’s evidence, was a mixture of financial, verbal and physical abuse. This was a not a key feature of the father’s case and little attention was directed towards it. In any case, the evidence is not sufficient to enable me to make a finding that the father was subjected to family violence. Any claims of financial abuse arising from the mother attempting to assist with the father’s gambling does not withstand scrutiny where there was clearly an agreement between the parties that she was to do that.

Consideration

I find that the father did perpetrate significant family violence against the mother and the child. The father in submissions made on his behalf has incorrectly adopted a particularly narrow view of what constitutes family violence. It is asserted that whilst there were instances of family violence directed at the mother, it was not directed towards the child. The child was certainly exposed to family violence within the meaning of s 4AB(3) of the Act.
Concerningly, the father has demonstrated a significant lack of insight into his actions. He has either denied that he has committed family violence or attempted to qualify his actions. This includes labelling verbal abuse as “just words” or attempting to frame himself as being the victim of family violence such as the April 2021 incident. The findings of family violence are significant. They involve a wide range of abuse directed towards the mother. Even when the father attempted to explain the 31 October 2020 incident, on his own case, it still involved him grabbing the mother’s throat.
Notwithstanding the fact that the father may have previously engaged in an anger management course as part of criminal proceedings, I have no confidence that he can safely parent the child. My findings of family violence above, coupled with his lack of insight, go to informing the possibility of harm arising if the child spends unsupervised time with the father, and the high possibility of harm in the father’s care is such that it presents as an unacceptable risk to the child. It also places the mother in a position where she will likely experience further family violence where the father will be able to act in a manner consistent with his past conduct without any safeguards. The father’s behaviour is unregulated, and he will expose the child to such. His past conduct is indicative that he is unable to control himself, particularly in times of heightened stress, and he lashes out verbally and physically. Given the child’s complex needs, which the father had little knowledge of despite his assertions otherwise, this makes the possibility of the father lashing out more likely where he has not demonstrated an understanding of how to deal with the child’s needs, noting that it has been several years since he has seen the child and during the marriage the mother was the primary carer.
Turning now to what, if any, conditions could be placed to ameliorate the risk to the child in spending time with the father, the evidence does not support a finding that supervision could ameliorate the risk identified to an acceptable level.
I have no confidence that the father will accept the authority of a supervisor to protect the child or to behave in an appropriate way with the child. His hatred of the mother is palpable, and I accept the mother's evidence that he has no respect for authority. His behaviour in court was such that he effectively disrespected the court process by failing to give frank and honest evidence by deliberately not answering questions in a truthful manner and engaging in outbursts when he became even slightly upset. His behaviour in relation to the workers from the DFFH was disgraceful in the way that he referred to them in highly racist and derogatory terms. When giving evidence, he gave the impression of being somewhat proud of his behaviour in that regard as he was entitled to speak that way to them because of what he perceived as their inappropriate actions.
Given the above, I do not accept that the father would be in any way respectful or responsive to a supervisor who took a different view to parenting than his approach. In fact, given his disposition during the hearing and my findings above, I find the possibility of the father lashing out towards any supervisor to be likely.
It was submitted on behalf of the father that where, again, there was no evidence that the father had directed family violence towards the child prior to separation or since and that given the father seeks orders that will keep the parents separate, this obviates the risk of exposure of the child to parental conflict. I do not accept this submission. The evidence is replete with examples of the father committing family violence on the mother in the presence of the child. As noted above, the father’s reliance on the mother's communications, including with the DFFH, where she is complimentary of the father or his parenting carries no weight. It was written at a time when she was under threat from the father and at a time where she was also financially reliant upon him. Again, the evidence is indicative of the father lacking insight into his behaviour and an inability to consistently act in an appropriate manner with authority figures. He has also demonstrated a history of committing family violence in the presence of the child and, despite frequent police and court intervention and the like, he has been either unable or unwilling to regulate his behaviour. In these circumstances, the Court has no confidence that father will be able to regulate his behaviour when spending time with the child, even if there was no contact between him and the mother and it occurred in the presence of the supervisor. In all likelihood, the father will treat any supervisor with the same contempt as he has demonstrated towards any form of authority during and prior to these proceedings and I find it unlikely that any supervisor will be able to assist in regulating the father’s behaviour.
I also find it likely that if orders were made for the father to spend time with the child, whether supervised or not, that the mother would be subjected to ongoing abuse and suffer the effects of such. I do not regard it as necessary to have expert opinion on the effects of family violence on the mother or the impacts of ongoing interaction with the father on her capacity to parent the child.
The Family Report writer produced a short form Family Report dated 20 February 2023 and a Family Report dated 30 October 2023. In her reports she sets out the mother’s allegations of family violence and the father’s responses. In the initial assessment, the Family Report writer expressed the opinion that the father may pose a significant risk of harm to the mother and child and that provisions needed to be made for their ongoing safety and protection: (at paragraph 115). She noted at paragraph 116, that throughout the assessment, the father had not demonstrated any remorse, insight or understanding into the impact of his behaviours but rather viewed himself as a victim. The Family Report writer recommended that the father's time remained suspended pending a forensic psychological or psychiatric assessment.
The psychiatric assessment was conducted by Dr C, and he produced a report dated 1 May 2023. At paragraph 74 of the report, Dr C states:
I have read the 69ZW report regarding DFFH involvement between November 2020 through to October 2021 with protective intervention with substantiated grounds with indications that the father, [Mr Preston], perpetrated family violence including threatening to stab the mother’s father with a knife, [Mr Preston] choking the mother with the mother holding the one-year-old child at the time, pulling the mother’s hair out, punching the mother on the left of the head.
At paragraph 83, Dr C stated:
This evaluation did not point to problems in the relationship with the child or in dealing with the child, although that issue needs to be addressed in a family report. Nevertheless, this evaluation does not exclude that relationships with the mother of the child could be affected by [Mr Preston’s] personality vulnerabilities, and it is highly likely that only parallel parenting will be appropriate. It is unlikely that [Mr Preston] will be able to negotiate effectively with his ex-partner and mother of the child at this point.
Dr C expressed the opinion that it may be of assistance that time between the father and the child as the Court considers appropriate is initially supervised and/or then in substantial attendance, moving to unsupervised time when positive time with the child is the identified.
In the course of oral evidence before the Court, Dr C revised his opinion in relation to the risk presented by the father and expressed that he presented a high level of risk to the mother and the child. It is noted that the report of Dr C relied heavily upon the father’s own self report regarding his relationship with his other children and his prior partner.
Following the receipt of Dr C’s assessment, the parties attended upon the Family Report writer for a Family Report. The father had expressed his dissatisfaction with the Family Report writer’s first report directly to the Family Report writer.
In the second family report, the Family Report writer noted at paragraph 165:
In making an assessment regarding [Mr Preston’s] potential risk to [X], it is possible that [Dr C] may not have received information that [X] is a special needs child with communication and speech delays who may required further assessment in relation to his symptoms of autism spectrum disorder. It is likely that this may be an additional consideration in relation to [Mr Preston’s] capacity to manage the behaviours of a child with additional emotional and psychological vulnerabilities.
The Family Report writer expressed real concerns regarding the father and his capacity, however, her recommendations were more directed as to whether the father's time should progress beyond supervised time as opposed to spending no time with his child. Having seen the father in the witness box and having read and considered all the evidence, I am firmly of the view that, on the basis of the material before the Court, it is in the best interest of the child that the father spends no time with the child. In assessing the evidence of the Family Report writer, I take into account that the father was highly critical of her after the production of the first report and that the Family Report writer terminated interviews with the father in the preparation of the second report because of his comments and behaviour. I also note that the report contained a minor error as to the father’s criminal history. I do not find that these matters have undermined the impartiality of the Family Report writer or that it has affected the quality or usefulness of the reports. I have observed the behaviour of the father in the course of the hearing, and I am able to form my own impression of him.
The Court has no confidence that any supervised time will be sufficiently managed or capable of being managed given the personality that the father has revealed through his evidence, through the expert reports and the multitude of information regarding his conduct.
This will have an impact on the child by significantly reducing the capacity for the child to have a relationship with the father and the paternal family, including his asserted cultural heritage through the paternal side, also noting that he has step-siblings. This much was said by the Family Report writer at paragraph 176 of the latest Family Report where it was noted that the assessment suggested that it is in the child’s best interests to be provided the opportunity to develop a relationship with the father to secure his own identity within a safe environment. While the Court is cognisant of this, when the matters of family violence are considered above and the father’s compromised capacity to provide for the child’s needs, any benefit to the child in having a relationship with the father is significantly outweighed by the unacceptable risk posed to the child in spending time with the father, supervised or unsupervised. The Court promotes children deriving benefit from healthy relationships with both parents, but not at the expense of their safety.
Unfortunately, this is a case where the risk to the child and the mother are such that the only arrangements which promote the child’s safety is one where there is no time between the father and the child. This was the position contended for by both the mother and the ICL and to which I agree.

Section 60CC(2)(b)

Any views expressed by the children

Given the age of the child, his views were not ascertained. The ICL did meet with the child. The notes recorded, as indicated by counsel for the ICL, that there was not much of substance gained from the meeting. The child said he did not remember the father’s name but knew that he was his father. The child then said that he remembered seeing the father and did miss him, but then also volunteered then he would not be happy to see him as he was a bad dad.
In any case, given the child’s age, I could place little weight on his views.

Section 60CC(2)(c)

The developmental, psychological, emotional and cultural needs of the child

As noted above, the child has been diagnosed with autism spectrum disorder and ADHD. He has also been diagnosed with a speech disorder. The child was diagnosed with eustachian tube dysfunction as an infant and in August 2023 commenced fortnightly sessions with a speech therapist. The child also attends upon a paediatrician every three months.[34] The mother gives evidence that the child has difficulty regulating his emotions and benefits from consistent routine.[35]

Section 60CC(2)(d)

The capacity of each person who has or is proposed to have parental responsibility for the child to provide for the child’s developmental, psychological, emotional and cultural needs

In his affidavit evidence the father had stated that he conducted research on the child's medical condition. In giving evidence to the Court, he accepted that he had not conducted any adequate research. His knowledge was limited to a conversation that he had with the father of a child who also attends the same school as the child. The information that he received was that the child attended a regular school without an aid. As result of his conversation with his friend, the father proffered the view that there was nothing much wrong with the child. In relation to this, and the discrepancy between the father’s evidence in his affidavit and his evidence before the Court during cross-examination, he stated that his legal team “put this together and I don’t want to get them into trouble”. He said in the witness box after being questioned, “I think I better do some research”.
The father gave evidence of his relationships with his other children and claimed that he had been hands on in his parenting with the child. The mother contests this and points to the substantial time that he spent at work socialising with his friends and gambling. For the reasons that I have outlined earlier in this judgment in relation to matters of credit, I prefer the evidence of the mother. The child has significant needs, and I did not get any sense that the father had any appreciation of the difficulties facing the challenges that gives rise to a parent. The point was made repeatedly to the father throughout the course of the hearing that the Court appreciated that the work that the father did was physically demanding and involved reasonably long hours. No explanation was provided by the father as to how he might manage to address the needs of the child if the orders that he was seeking were made.
The father had filed affidavit evidence of several individuals to give character evidence on his behalf. The father elected not to call those witnesses. This was in the context where I had raised with counsel for the father whether calling those witnesses was of any real benefit and made comment that the Court was not particularly interested in “barrackers”. That was a view endorsed by counsel for the father at that time. The interaction occurred as follows:
[Counsel for the father]: There are lay witnesses on my side of the court, people that attest to my client’s good character and the like.

His Honour: I’m not really interested in [barrackers].

[Counsel for the father]: No, neither am I, your Honour. But there they are.

His Honour: Well, give some consideration to all that.

(Transcript 11 July 2025, p 627 lines 39-46)
When the matter resumed, however, it was announced that the father would not be calling those witnesses because of the attitude I had evinced in my comments. In circumstances where counsel for the father had endorsed my remark, I reject any suggestion that the father was somehow unable to rely on the evidence of these people if he chose to do so. In any case, I concur with the comments of Aldridge J in Besim & Zehra (2025) FLC 94-274:
Glowing affidavits from family members and friends that take the form of character references or cheer squad support for the contentions of the party seeking to call them are generally not helpful in family law proceedings. They often tend to focus on opinion rather than observation and fact. Given the weight that they are likely to carry, even if ultimately accepted, they are rarely a benefit to proceedings.
There was no submission made that the mother was not capable either now or in the past of providing for the child's needs.

Section 60CC(2)(e)

The benefit to the child of being able to have a relationship with the child’s parents, and other people who are significant to the child, where it is safe to do so

The mother was adamant that she did not see any negatives in the child not seeing the father and she did not acknowledge that the father had a good relationship with the child or that he had a positive relationship with his other children. She also did not accept that he presented as a role model to the child by way of being a successful business owner.
In any case, the risk presented by the father outweighs any benefit for the child in spending time with him.

Section 60CC(2)(f)

Anything else that is relevant to the particular circumstances of the children

There is nothing further which is of relevance.

Parental Responsibility

For the reasons expressed above, the mother will have the sole care of the child, and the Court holds serious concerns about the father’s behaviour towards the mother, his lack of insight and perpetration of family violence. It is appropriate and in the best interests of the child that the mother have sole decision-making authority for long-term issues relating to the child without any need for consultation with the father.

Change of Name

The mother sought orders that she be permitted to change the child’s surname to “[Scriven]” instead of “[Preston]”. In support of this, she submitted that Y’s surname is Scriven and the child knows himself as Scriven.[36]
I refer to the helpful summary of Austin J in Dematos & Burellis [2025] FedCFamC1F 471 in dealing with such matters:
Any decision about the name by which a child should be known is dictated by the child’s best interests (Reynolds & Sherman [2015] FamCAFC 128; (2015) 297 FLR 349 at [54]–[55]). There is no onus of proof. The decision is discretionary and is informed by such considerations as the degree of the child’s identification with the existing surname and any difficulty or embarrassment the child may experience by using the same or a different surname. The list of factors is not exhaustive (Flanagan v Handcock (2001) FLC 93-074 at [19]–[38]; M v B [2001] FamCA 894 at [35]–[37]; Marriage of Mahony & McKenzie [1993] FamCA 78; (1993) 16 Fam LR 803; Chapman v Palmer [1978] FamCA 86; (1978) 4 Fam LR 462).
The child will be in the sole care of the mother whose surname is “[Scriven]”. Y, who he also lives with, surname is also “[Scriven]”. It is likely to cause embarrassment and confusion to the child to have a different surname and in circumstances where the Family Report writer has found it likely that the child has little memory of the father. The Court has also found that the father presents such an unacceptable risk to the child that there is little benefit in the child maintaining a significant relationship with him when compared to the unacceptable risk that he poses and, in these circumstances, it is appropriate that there be an order for the mother to be permitted to change the child’s name. Instead, the father may maintain some relationship with the child through the provision of cards, letters and gifts, providing that they are appropriate for the child.

CONCLUSION

The Court will make orders to give effect to these findings.
